{{head|fr|prepositions}}

# [[in]] {{gloss|used to indicate space, also see usage notes}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|J'habite '''en''' Angleterre.|I live in England.}}
# [[to]] {{gloss|indicates direction towards certain very large locations, see usage notes}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|Il est allé '''en''' France.|He went to France.}}
# [[by]] {{gloss|used to indicate means}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|aller '''en''' bus|go by bus}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|partir '''en''' voiture|leave by car}}
# [[as]]
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|Il me traite '''en''' ami.|He treats me as a friend.}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|habillé '''en''' père Noël|dressed as Father Christmas}}
# [[at]] {{gloss|used to describe an ability}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|fort '''en''' histoire|good at history}}
# [[of]], made of {{gloss|used to describe composition}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|une chaise '''en''' hêtre|a chair made of beech/a beech chair}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|une fourchette '''en''' métal|a fork made of metal/a metal fork}}
# [[in]] {{gloss|during the following time (used for months and years)}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|'''en''' 1993|'''in''' 1993}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|'''en''' janvier|'''in''' January}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|'''en''' septembre 2001|'''in''' September 2001}}
# {{lb|fr|followed by a [[gerund]]}} [[while]]
# {{lb|fr|followed by a [[gerund]]}} [[by]], [[in]] {{gloss|describing a way of getting something}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|C'est '''en''' trichant qu'il est devenu champion.|It was '''by''' cheating that he became champion.}}
# [[in]] {{gloss|used to describe color}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|une photo '''en''' noir et blanc|a photo '''in''' black and white}}
# [[in]] {{gloss|used to describe feelings}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|'''en''' détresse|'''in''' distress}}
# [[in]] {{gloss|as part of something}}
#: {{ux|fr|inline=1|'''en''' équipe|'''on''' a team}}

=====Usage notes=====
* {{m|fr|en|En}} in the sense of ''while'' is often not translated into English.
* When referring to location in countries, provinces, or similar subdivisions in sense 1 and direction in sense 2, {{m|fr|en}} must be used when the name for that very large location is either a feminine singular noun or a vowel-initial masculine singular noun. If the name for the very large location is a consonant-initial masculine singular noun, {{m|fr|au}} is used, while if the name of the very large location is plural, {{m|fr|aux}} is used.

